      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You quote Senator Paul Wellstone of Minnesota as saying (front page, April 24) that "reatment of mental illness not only saves lives, but it also saves dollars," because "people cured of mental illness can be more productive workers."</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You quote Senator Paul Wellstone of Minnesota as saying (front page, April 24) that "reatment of mental illness not only saves lives, but it also saves dollars," because "people cured of mental illness can be more productive workers."</p>
        <p>There are no cures for mental illness, only treatment, which is usually drugs. This is one reason that widening insurance coverage to include mental health care would increase health costs at least as much as the Congressional Budget Office warned.</p>
        <p>Mental health care only treats the disease or illness; it does not remove it. Whether depression, schizophrenia or even chronic unhappiness, the health insurance bill provides virtually endless treatment for these and other mental conditions and if enacted will bankrupt businesses and insurers.</p>
        <p>RONALD P. KLIPSTEIN New York, April 25, 1996</p>
      </block>
